6 INTERSTATE ACTIONS
7
8 SECTION 1. Policy regarding legal protections for reproductive or gender-affirming
9 health care activities. (1) “Gender-affirming treatment” and “reproductive health care” have
10 the meanings given those terms in ORS 24.500.
11 (2) It is the policy of this state that people should be protected under state law to engage
12 in the following activities related to reproductive health care or gender-affirming treatment
13 that is provided by a health care provider who is licensed in this state, who is acting within
14 the health care provider’s scope of practice and who provides or attempts to provide the
15 reproductive health care or gender-affirming treatment to a patient who is physically located
16 in this state:
17 (a) The receipt or attempted receipt of reproductive health care or gender-affirming
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 49

A-Eng. HB 4088
1 treatment that is lawful in this state.
2 (b) The provision or attempted provision of reproductive health care or gender-affirming
3 treatment that is lawful in this state.
4 (c) The assistance or attempted assistance in the receipt or provision of reproductive
5 health care or gender-affirming treatment that is lawful in this state.
6 SECTION 2. Nonfugitive extradition. (1) As used in this section, “legally-protected re-
7 productive or gender-affirming health care activities” means one or more of the activities
8 described in section 1 of this 2026 Act.
9 (2) Except as required by federal law and notwithstanding ORS 133.767, the Governor of
10 this state may not surrender, on demand of the executive authority of any other state, a
11 person in this state charged in such other state for engaging in legally-protected reproduc-
12 tive or gender-affirming health care activities if the Governor is not otherwise required to
13 surrender the person under ORS 133.747.
14 SECTION 3. Cooperation with federal and interstate investigations. (1) As used in this
15 section:
16 (a) “Legally-protected reproductive or gender-affirming health care activities” means one
17 or more of the activities described in section 1 of this 2026 Act.
18 (b) “Public body” means a public body as defined in ORS 174.109 and the Oregon Health
19 and Science University.
20 (2)(a) Except as provided in ORS 24.500 and 133.747, or as required by federal law, an of-
21 ficer, employee or agent of a public body may not cooperate with, provide information to or
22 otherwise expend or use time, moneys, facilities, property, equipment, personnel or other
23 resources to assist a federal law enforcement agency, a law enforcement agency of another
24 state, a private citizen or a quasi-law enforcement agent in relation to an investigation or
25 inquiry into a legally-protected reproductive or gender-affirming health care activity, if such
26 activity would be lawful if it occurred entirely in this state.
27 (b) Nothing in this subsection prohibits an officer, employee or agent of a public body
28 from disclosing information that is responsive to an investigation or inquiry described in
29 paragraph (a) of this subsection to the extent the information is available to the general
30 public provided the disclosure is made under the same terms and conditions as the informa-
31 tion is made available to the general public.
