36 MALPRACTICE INSURANCE AND LICENSING
37
38 SECTION 14. ORS 676.612, as operative until July 1, 2026, is amended to read:
39 676.612. (1) Subject to ORS 676.616 and 687.445, and in the manner prescribed in ORS chapter
40 183 for contested cases and as specified in ORS 675.385, 676.660, 676.685, 676.745, 676.777, 676.825,
41 678.780, 680.535, 681.733, 681.755, 687.445, 688.734, 688.836, 690.167, 690.407, 691.477, 694.147 and
42 700.111, the Health Licensing Office may refuse to issue or renew, may suspend or revoke or may
43 otherwise condition or limit an authorization or may discipline or place on probation an authori-
44 zation holder for commission of the prohibited acts listed in subsection (2) of this section.
45 (2) A person subject to the authority of a board, council or program listed in ORS 676.565
[12]

A-Eng. HB 4088
1 commits a prohibited act if the person engages in:
2 (a) Fraud, misrepresentation, concealment of material facts or deception in applying for or ob-
3 taining an authorization to practice in this state, or in any written or oral communication to the
4 office concerning the issuance or retention of the authorization.
5 (b) Using, causing or promoting the use of any advertising matter, promotional literature, testi-
6 monial, guarantee, warranty, label, insignia or any other representation, however disseminated or
7 published, that is false, misleading or deceptive.
8 (c) Making a representation that the authorization holder knew or should have known is false
9 or misleading regarding skill or the efficacy or value of treatment or remedy administered by the
10 authorization holder.
11 (d) Practicing under a false, misleading or deceptive name, or impersonating another authori-
12 zation holder.
13 (e) Permitting a person other than the authorization holder to use the authorization.
14 (f) Practicing with a physical or mental condition that presents an unreasonable risk of harm
15 to the authorization holder or to the person or property of others in the course of performing the
16 authorization holder’s duties.
17 (g) Practicing while under the influence of alcohol, cannabis, controlled substances or other
18 skill-impairing substances, or engaging in the illegal use of controlled substances or other skill-
19 impairing substances so as to create a risk of harm to the person or property of others in the course
20 of performing the duties of an authorization holder.
21 (h) Failing to properly and reasonably accept responsibility for the actions of employees.
22 (i) Employing, directly or indirectly, any suspended, uncertified, unlicensed or unregistered per-
23 son to practice a regulated occupation or profession subject to the authority of the boards, councils
24 and programs listed in ORS 676.565.
25 (j) Unprofessional conduct, negligence, incompetence, repeated violations or any departure from
26 or failure to conform to standards of practice in performing services or practicing in a regulated
27 occupation or profession subject to the authority of the boards, councils and programs listed under
28 ORS 676.565.
29 (k) Except as provided in ORS 687.445, conviction of any criminal offense, subject to ORS
30 670.280. A copy of the record of conviction, certified by the clerk of the court entering the con-
31 viction, is conclusive evidence of the conviction. A plea of no contest or an admission of guilt is a
32 conviction for purposes of this paragraph.
33 (L) Failing to report any adverse action, as required by statute or rule, taken against the au-
34 thorization holder by another regulatory jurisdiction or any peer review body, health care institu-
35 tion, professional association, governmental agency, law enforcement agency or court for acts or
36 conduct similar to acts or conduct that would constitute grounds for disciplinary action as described
37 in this section.
38 (m) Violation of a statute regulating an occupation or profession subject to the authority of the
39 boards, councils and programs listed in ORS 676.565.
40 (n) Violation of any rule regulating an occupation or profession subject to the authority of the
41 boards, councils and programs listed in ORS 676.565.
42 (o) Failing to cooperate with the office in any investigation, inspection or request for informa-
43 tion.
44 (p) Selling or fraudulently obtaining or furnishing an authorization to practice in a regulated
45 occupation or profession subject to the authority of the boards, councils and programs listed in ORS
[13]

A-Eng. HB 4088
1 676.565, or aiding or abetting such an act.
2 (q) Selling or fraudulently obtaining or furnishing any record related to practice in a regulated
3 occupation or profession subject to the authority of the boards, councils and programs listed in ORS
4 676.565, or aiding or abetting such an act.
5 (r) Failing to pay an outstanding civil penalty or fee that is due or failing to meet the terms of
6 any order issued by the office that has become final.
7 (3) For the purpose of requesting a state or nationwide criminal records check under ORS
8 181A.195, the office may require the fingerprints of a person who is:
9 (a) Applying for an authorization;
10 (b) Applying for renewal of an authorization; or
11 (c) Under investigation by the office.
12 (4) If the office places an authorization holder on probation under subsection (1) of this section,
13 the office, in consultation with the appropriate board, council or program, may determine and at any
14 time modify the conditions of the probation.
15 (5) If an authorization is suspended, the authorization holder may not practice during the term
16 of suspension. Upon the expiration of the term of suspension, the authorization may be reinstated
17 by the office if the conditions of suspension no longer exist and the authorization holder has satis-
18 fied all requirements in the relevant statutes or administrative rules for issuance, renewal or rein-
19 statement.
